ðŸ” API Testing â€“ Interview Questions & Answers
ðŸ”¹ Q1: What is API Security Testing?
A: API Security Testing involves checking the security posture of Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) to identify vulnerabilities such as broken authentication, improper access controls, insecure data exposure, and injection flaws.

ðŸ”¹ Q2: What are common API vulnerabilities?
A:

Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA/IDOR)

Broken Authentication

Excessive Data Exposure

Mass Assignment

Injection Attacks (SQLi, XSS, JSONi)

Rate Limiting Bypass

Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)

Improper Asset Management

Lack of Logging and Monitoring

ðŸ”¹ Q3: How do you test for BOLA / IDOR in APIs?
A:

Change the user_id, file_id, account_id in the request:

http
Copy
Edit
GET /api/user/1234
Try accessing another userâ€™s data:

http
Copy
Edit
GET /api/user/1235
If access is granted â†’ Vulnerable to IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference)

ðŸ”¹ Q4: How do you test for API authentication weaknesses?
A:

Check for:

Weak or missing tokens

Predictable or reusable tokens

JWT tampering (none alg, invalid signature)

Use expired/forged tokens

Try login brute-force or token leakage from responses

ðŸ”¹ Q5: What is mass assignment in API security?
A: If an API blindly accepts user-supplied JSON, attackers can overwrite fields like isAdmin, role, etc.

Example:

json
Copy
Edit
POST /api/user/update
{
  "username": "user",
  "isAdmin": true
}
âž¡ï¸ If isAdmin is not filtered, attacker becomes admin.

Mitigation: Whitelist allowed fields on backend.

ðŸ”¹ Q6: How do you detect excessive data exposure?
A:

Review JSON responses.

Check if the API exposes internal fields:

password_hash, isAdmin, internalId, debugData, etc.

If frontend hides it but backend exposes it = problem.

ðŸ”¹ Q7: How to test for rate limiting issues?
A:

Send multiple requests rapidly using tools like:

Burp Intruder, ffuf, Turbo Intruder, Postman

Check if:

Brute-force login is possible

No 429 Too Many Requests error

CAPTCHA is missing or ineffective

ðŸ”¹ Q8: What tools do you use for API testing?
A:

Burp Suite â€“ manual + automated testing

Postman â€“ manual testing + scripting

OWASP ZAP â€“ scanner + fuzzing

Insomnia, Hoppscotch â€“ alternatives to Postman

ffuf, nuclei, jwt_tool, ParamMiner, jwt-cracker â€“ for automation

ðŸ”¹ Q9: How do you test for insecure HTTP methods?
A:

Use curl or Burp:

bash
Copy
Edit
curl -X OPTIONS https://example.com/api/
If methods like PUT, DELETE, TRACE are enabled, check for misuse.

ðŸ”¹ Q10: What are security headers important for API responses?
A:

Content-Security-Policy (CSP)

Strict-Transport-Security

X-Frame-Options

Access-Control-Allow-Origin (CORS)

X-Content-Type-Options

Missing or misconfigured headers can lead to:

Clickjacking

XSS

CORS abuse

ðŸ”¹ Q11: How do you test for CORS misconfiguration in APIs?
A:

Send request with:

http
Copy
Edit
Origin: evil.com
If response includes:

yaml
Copy
Edit
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
âž¡ï¸ Itâ€™s vulnerable.

ðŸ”¹ Q12: How do you test JWT vulnerabilities?
A:

Check for:

None algorithm attack (alg: none)

Weak secret bruteforcing (use jwt_tool, john)

Payload tampering

Expired or reused JWT

ðŸ”¹ Q13: What is API versioning abuse?
A: If older API versions are still accessible (e.g., /v1/api/user), and vulnerable, attackers can target those endpoints even if the frontend uses /v3.

âž¡ï¸ Always test deprecated versions.

ðŸ”¹ Q14: What are common attack payloads for APIs?
A:

SQLi: ' OR 1=1--

XSS: "><script>alert(1)</script>

SSRF: http://127.0.0.1:80/

JSONi: { "$ne": null }

JWT None: { "alg": "none" }

Broken auth: Try token swapping or bypassing MFA

ðŸ”¹ Q15: What is the OWASP API Top 10?
A:

API1 â€“ Broken Object Level Authorization

API2 â€“ Broken Authentication

API3 â€“ Excessive Data Exposure

API4 â€“ Lack of Resources & Rate Limiting

API5 â€“ Broken Function Level Authorization

API6 â€“ Mass Assignment

API7 â€“ Security Misconfiguration

API8 â€“ Injection

API9 â€“ Improper Asset Management

API10 â€“ Insufficient Logging & Monitoring

